public static class JsGlobal.Date
extends JsFunction<java.lang.String>

An opaque class representing the global Date class of JavaScript.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
JavaScript:
Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be generated into the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on the operations of accessing that kind of class objects. The checkcast operation to the class literal of this interface must be ignored and instanceof to it always true.

Method Detail

parse

public final java.lang.Number parse(java.lang.Object v)

Parses a string representation of a date and time and returns the internal millisecond representation of that date.

Note that, in JavaScript Date.parse() is "static" method of the global class Date, but in JS this method is of an instance.

Date.parse() is a static method of Date. It is always invoked through the Date constructor as Date.parse(), not through a Date object as date.parse(). Date.parse() takes a single string argument. It parses the date contained in this string and returns it in millisecond format, which can be used directly, used to create a new Date object, or used to set the date in an existing Date object with JsDate.setTime(Object).

The ECMAScript standard does not specify the format of the strings that can be parsed by this method except to say that this method can parse the strings returned by the JsObject.toString() and JsDate.toUTCString() methods. Unfortunately, these functions format dates in an implementation-dependent way, so it is not, in general, possible to write dates in a way that is guaranteed to be understood by all JavaScript implementations.

Parameters:
v - A string containing the date and time to be parsed.
Returns:
The number of milliseconds between the specified date and time and midnight GMT on January 1, 1970.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
parse(Object)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must replace the instance invocation of this method with the JavaScript expression: 
Date.parse(v)

UTC

public final java.lang.Number UTC(java.lang.Object yr,
                                  java.lang.Object mo)

Returns the millisecond representation of the specified UTC date and time.

Note that, in JavaScript Date.UTC() is "static" method of the global class Date; it is invoked through the Date() constructor, not through an individual Date object. However, in JS this method is of an instance.

The arguments to this method specify a date and time and are understood to be in UTC; they are in the GMT time zone. The specified UTC time is converted to the millisecond format, which can be used by the JsDate constructor methods and by the JsDate.setTime(Object) method.

The JsDate constructor methods can accept date and time arguments identical to those that this method accepts. The difference is that JsDate constructors assume local time, while this method assumes universal time (GMT).

Parameters:
yr - The year in four-digit format. If this argument is between 0 and 99, inclusive, 1900 is added to it and it is treated as a year between 1900 and 1999.
mo - The month, specified as an integer from 0 (January) to 11 (December).
Returns:
The millisecond representation of the specified universal time. That is, this method returns the number of milliseconds between midnight GMT on January 1, 1970 and the specified time.
Since:
1.0
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must replace the instance invocation of this method with the JavaScript expression: 
Date.UTC(yr, mo)

create

public final JsDate create(java.lang.Object yr,
                           java.lang.Object mo)

Constructs a date object with two to seven numeric arguments that specify the individual fields of the date and time. All but the first two arguments, the year and month fields, are optional.

Note that these date and time fields are specified using local time, not Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) (which is similar to Greenwich Mean Time [GMT]). See the static UTC(Object, Object)method for an alternative.

In JavaScript, Date() may also be called as a function, without the new operator. When invoked in this way, Date() ignores any arguments passed to it and returns a string representation of the current date and time.

Parameters:
yr - The year, in four-digit format. For compatibility with early implementations of JavaScript, if this argument is between 0 and 99, 1900 is added to it.
mo - The month, specified as an integer from 0 (January) to 11 (December).
Returns:
The newly constructed date object.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
JsDate.JsDate(Object, Object)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must replace the instance invocation of this method with the JavaScript expression: 
new Date(yr, mo)

create

public final JsDate create(java.lang.Object yr,
                           java.lang.Object mo,
                           java.lang.Object day,
                           java.lang.Object hr,
                           java.lang.Object min)

Constructs a date object with two to seven numeric arguments that specify the individual fields of the date and time. All but the first two arguments, the year and month fields, are optional.

Note that these date and time fields are specified using local time, not Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) (which is similar to Greenwich Mean Time [GMT]). See the static UTC(Object, Object)method for an alternative.

In JavaScript, Date() may also be called as a function, without the new operator. When invoked in this way, Date() ignores any arguments passed to it and returns a string representation of the current date and time.

Parameters:
yr - The year, in four-digit format. For compatibility with early implementations of JavaScript, if this argument is between 0 and 99, 1900 is added to it.
mo - The month, specified as an integer from 0 (January) to 11 (December).
day - The day of the month, specified as an integer from 1 to 31. Note that this argument uses 1 as its lowest value, while other arguments use 0 as their lowest value. Optional.
hr - The hour, specified as an integer from 0 (midnight) to 23 (11 p.m.). Optional.
min - The minutes in the hour, specified as an integer from 0 to 59. Optional.
Returns:
The newly constructed date object.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
JsDate.JsDate(Object, Object, Object, Object, Object)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must replace the instance invocation of this method with the JavaScript expression: 
new Date(yr, mo, day, hr, min)
